# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asian-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The **1906 Intercalated Games** or **1906 Olympic Games** (Greek: Μεσολυμπιάδα, romanized: *Mesolympiada*, lit.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] 'Mesolympics'), held from 22 April 1906 to 2 May 1906, was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated in Athens, Greece.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] It was at the time considered to be part of the series of the Olympic Games, and was referred to as the "Second International Olympic Games in Athens" by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its influence on the Olympic tradition and the records broken during these Games are recorded in history, but are no longer considered part of the Olympic records.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] 894 athletes from 20 nations competed in this competition.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The idea behind the Intercalated Games was to have an Olympics in Greece every four years, but this would be the first and last.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The idea was not pursued further, and is sometimes termed the "forgotten Games" in the context of the Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The next Olympic Games was the 1908 Summer Olympics in London; the next time the Olympic Games returned to Greece was 98 years later in 2004, also in Athens.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The Intercalated Olympic Games were to be a series of *International Olympic Games* halfway between what is now known as the Games of the Olympiad, old and new.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] This proposed series of Games, intercalated in the Olympic Games cycle, was always to be held in Athens and was to have equal status with the international Games.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] However, the only such Games was held in 1906.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] One reason for the Games in 1906 was to celebrate the tenth anniversary of the 1896 Games.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The first Intercalated Games had been scheduled by the International Olympic Committee in 1901 as part of a new schedule, where every four years, in between the internationally organised Games, there would be an Intermediate Games held in Athens.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] This was a compromise; after the successful Games of Athens 1896, the Greeks suggested they could organise the Games every four years.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] Since they had the accommodation and had proven they could hold well-organised Games, they received substantial public support.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] However, Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the International Olympic Committee, opposed this, as he had intended for the first Games to be in Paris in 1900.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] After Paris had lost the première Olympics, De Coubertin did not want the Games to be permanently hosted elsewhere.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The 1900 Games were overshadowed by the Exposition Universelle, whose organising committee disagreed with De Coubertin's ideas to such an extent that he resigned.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The organisation of the 1900 Games was haphazard by today's standards, and although some events, such as archery, drew widespread attention, many others were poorly attended.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] Historians' opinions still differ over which events should be considered "Olympic".
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] Consequently, the IOC supported the Greek idea by granting them a second series of quadrennial Games in between the first series.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] This was a departure from the ancient schedule, but it was expected that, if the ancient Greeks could keep a four-year schedule, the modern Olympic Movement could keep a two-year schedule.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] As 1902 was now too close to be logistically workable, and Greece was experiencing political and economic difficulties, the 2nd Olympic Games in Athens were scheduled for 1906, and the IOC as a whole gave Greece full support for the organisation.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, Missouri were overshadowed by the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, and their organisation was even worse than that of Paris 1900, while travel difficulties meant that only 20% of the athletes were non-American; of these, half were Canadian.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] It was clear the Olympic Movement was in a dire situation and desperately needed to recapture the spirit of Athens 1896.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] It also needed to do so quickly, as to those who did not participate in St.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, 1908 was a gap of eight years, by which time there would be little, if any, goodwill left for the Games.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] To make matters worse, Rome, the proposed host for 1908, was also planning an exhibition at the same time as the Games, which had been responsible for the failures of Paris and St.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] To the IOC, the 1906 Athens Games being just around the corner would have been a lifeline.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] While De Coubertin still opposed the idea and did not do anything more than his function required of him, the IOC as a whole gave the Greek organising committee full support for the organisation.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] These games offered Greece the huge opportunity to show that it was important to Europe's present and its past.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] It is clear from the beginning that the Olympic Games 1906 became "a grand project far beyond the status of a mere sports meeting", with new structures built to accommodate the events including the restoration of the ancient stadium in Athens.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games were quite successful: unlike the Games of 1900, 1904 or 1908, they were not stretched out over several months, and unlike 1900 and 1904, they were not overshadowed by an international exposition.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] Their crisp implementation was most likely instrumental in the continued existence of the Games.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] These, along with various other changes, are now accepted as tradition.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The Games were held from 22 April to 2 May 1906, in Athens, Greece.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] They took place in the Panathenaic Stadium, which had already hosted the 1896 Games and the earlier Zappas Olympics of 1870 and 1875.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The Games excluded several disciplines that had occurred during the past two Games; it was unclear whether they ought to have been part of the Olympic Games.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] Added to the program were the javelin throw and the pentathlon.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its opening and closing ceremonies, which initiated this tradition.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] The 1908 Games introduced the tradition of the host coming in as the last in the parade also.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] These were the first Games to include an opening ceremony with athletes marching into the stadium as national teams behind their flags.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] King George I officially opened the Games.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] Six thousand schoolchildren took part in the first ever Olympic closing ceremony.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] 854 athletes, 848 men and six women, from 20 countries, competed at the 1906 Intercalated Games.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] 78 events in 14 disciplines, comprising 12 sports, were part of the 1906 Games.
[src:asian-games/1906-intercalated-games] These medals were distributed but are no longer recognized by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:asian-games/1913-far-eastern-games] The **1st Far Eastern Championship Games** were held in 1–9 February 1913 in Manila, Philippines.
[src:asian-games/1913-far-eastern-games] The inaugural tournament was officially opened by Governor General William Cameron Forbes at the Carnival Grounds in Malate, Manila.
[src:asian-games/1913-far-eastern-games] Six countries participated at the tournament.
[src:asian-games/1913-far-eastern-games] The Olympic Council of Asia also claimed that Federated Malay States, Siam, Hong Kong also took part in the event.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] The **1934 Far Eastern Championship Games** was the tenth edition of the regional multi-sport event, contested between China, Japan and the Philippines, and was held from 16 to 20 May in Manila, the Philippines.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] A total of eight sports were contested during the four-day competition.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] The Dutch East Indies (Indonesia) participated in the games, becoming only the second nation outside of the traditional three to send a delegation to the event (after India in 1930).
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] The games were held at the then newly built sports complex, Rizal Memorial Field which was constructed on the former site of the Manila Carnival Grounds.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] Official women's events were featured on the programme for the first time.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] Although some women's activities had been included since 1921, this marked the first occasion that women's sports were given parity with men's contest and was treated as part of the official medal count and points tables.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] The swimming programme featured at least four different events for women.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] China won its ninth straight title in the football competition.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] This was the last Far Eastern Championship Games.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] Poor relations between China and Japan disrupted the working of the Far Eastern Athletic Association (the organising body for the games).
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] Before the games, Japanese delegations repeatedly suggested to the Chinese that Manchukuo compete as an independent team at the forthcoming competition.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] This greatly angered the Chinese, given that Manchukuo had been operated as a puppet state following the Japanese invasion of Manchuria in 1931.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] The 11th Far Eastern Championship Games was scheduled to be held in 1938 in Osaka, Japan, but was cancelled after the 1937 outbreak of the Second Sino-Japanese War.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] Given the warring of two of its three member nations, the Far Eastern Athletic Association was rendered defunct.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] The holding of the first Western Asiatic Games in 1934 demonstrated an increasing desire for Asian-led international multi-sport events.
[src:asian-games/1934-far-eastern-games] Following the end of World War II, the Asian Games was created in 1951 and featured two of the former Far Eastern groups – Japan and the Philippines.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The **1948 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XIV Olympiad** and officially branded as **London 1948**, were an international multi-sport event held from 29 July to 14 August 1948 in London, United Kingdom.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Following a twelve-year hiatus caused by the outbreak of World War II, these were the first Summer Olympics held since the 1936 Games in Berlin.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1940 Olympic Games had been scheduled for Tokyo and then for Helsinki, while the 1944 Olympic Games had been provisionally planned for London.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] This was the second time London hosted the Olympic Games, having previously hosted them in 1908, making it the second city to host the Summer Olympics twice (after Paris).
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The Olympics would return again to London 64 years later in 2012, making London the first city to host the games three times, and the only such city until Paris, who hosted their third games in 2024, and Los Angeles, who will host theirs in 2028.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Olympic Games were also the first of two summer Games held under the IOC presidency of Sigfrid Edström.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Summer Olympics were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1940s, as the 1940 and 1944 Summer Olympics were cancelled due to World War II.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] It was also the first Summer Olympics that took place during the Cold War.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Olympics came to be known as the "Austerity Games" due to the difficult economic climate and the rationing imposed in the aftermath of World War II.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] A record 59 nations were represented by 4,104 athletes, 3,714 men, and 390 women in 19 sport disciplines.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Germany and Japan were not invited to participate in the games; the Soviet Union was invited but chose not to send any athletes, sending observers instead to prepare for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Israel requested to participate (symbolically represented by Raya Bronstein and Frieda Berson-Lichtblau) but was denied as the International Olympic Committee did not yet recognize the country, while the Olympic mandate of Palestine expired.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] This in turn shifted the view of the Arab countries who had intended to boycott the event and now decided to take part.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] One of the star performers at the 1948 Games was Dutch sprinter Fanny Blankers-Koen.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Dubbed the "Flying Housewife", the thirty-year-old mother of two won four gold medals in athletics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the decathlon, Bob Mathias of the United States became the youngest male ever to win an Olympic track and field gold medal at the age of seventeen.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The most individual medals were won by Veikko Huhtanen of Finland, who took three golds, a silver and a bronze in men's gymnastics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The United States topped the medal table.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In June 1939, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) awarded the 1944 Olympic Summer Games to London, ahead of Rome, Detroit, Budapest, Lausanne, Helsinki, Montreal and Athens.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] World War II stopped the plans and the Games were cancelled so London again stood as a candidate for 1948.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Great Britain almost handed the 1948 games to the United States due to post-war financial and rationing problems, but King George VI said that hosting the Olympics would help to restore Britain from World War II.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The official report of the London Olympics shows that London was not pressed to run the Games against its will.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] and saw the president of the International Olympic Committee to discuss the question of London being chosen for this great event.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] As a result, an investigating committee was set up by the British Olympic Council to work out in some detail the possibility of holding the Games.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] should be invited to apply for the allocation of the Games in 1948.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In June 1946 the IOC, through a postal vote, gave the summer Games to London and the winter competition to St Moritz.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] London was selected ahead of Baltimore, Minneapolis, Lausanne, Los Angeles, and Philadelphia.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] London, which had previously hosted the 1908 Summer Olympics, became the second city to host the Olympics twice; Paris hosted the event in 1900 and 1924.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] London later became the first city to host the Olympics for a third time when the city hosted the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Lord Burghley, a gold medal winner at the 1928 Olympics, member of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), and president of the Amateur Athletics Association was named Chairman of the Organising and Executive Committees.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The other members of the committees were: Colonel Evan Hunter, General Secretary of the British Olympic Association, and Chief de mission for Great Britain; Lord Aberdare, the other British member of the IOC; Sir Noel Curtis-Bennett; Alderman H.E.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Emrys Lloyd, who became the committee's legal advisor; C.B.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Cowley of the London Press and Advertising; R.B.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Studdert, managing director of the Army & Navy Stores; A.E.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Porritt, a member of the IOC for New Zealand who resided in London; S.F.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Rous, Secretary of The Football Association; and Jack Beresford.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Olympic pictograms were introduced for the first time.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] There were twenty of them—one for each Olympic sport and three separate pictograms for the arts competition, the opening ceremony and the closing ceremony.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] They were called "Olympic symbols" and intended for use on tickets.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The background of each pictogram resembled an escutcheon.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Olympic pictograms appeared again 16 years later, and were used at all subsequent Summer Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] At the time of the Games, food, petrol and building were still subject to the rationing imposed during the war in Britain; because of this the 1948 Olympics came to be known as the "Austerity Games".
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Athletes were given the same increased rations as dockers and miners, 5,467 calories a day instead of the normal 2,600.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Building an Olympic Village was deemed too expensive, and athletes were housed in existing accommodation.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Male competitors stayed at RAF camps in Uxbridge and West Drayton, and an Army camp in Richmond Park; female competitors in London colleges.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Lord Burghley unfurled the Olympic Flag at the Richmond Park camp at an opening ceremony in July as Minister of Works, Charles Key, declared the camp open.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] These were the first games to be held following the death of Pierre de Coubertin, founder of the International Olympic Committee, in 1937.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] They were also the last to include an arts competition, which took place at the Victoria and Albert Museum.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Nicknamed "relay of peace" due to crossing through several countries in Europe to represent their union after the Second World War, the torch relay for these games took place from 17 to 29 July 1948, with a distance of 3,160 kilometres (1,960 mi) and 1,416 torchbearers.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] There were three types of torches: the standard one made of aluminium and powered by solid fuel, a special one powered by butane gas (used aboard HMS *Whitesand Bay*) and a third one used in the Wembley stadium, made of stainless steel and powered by a magnesium candle.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The journey began with the lighting of the flame in Olympia.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Due to the civil war taking place in Greece, the Greek part of the relay went directly to Corfu, where HMS *Whitesand Bay* picked the flame to transport it to Bari.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] From there, the flame crossed Italy, Switzerland, France, Luxembourg and Belgium.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] After a boat trip from Calais to Dover (aboard of HMS *Bicester*), the flame traveled to several towns in Southeast England until the arrival at Wembley for the Opening ceremony.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Army bands began playing at 2 pm for the 85,000 spectators in Empire Stadium at Wembley Park.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The international and national organisers arrived at 2.35 pm and King George VI and Queen Elizabeth, with Queen Mary and other members of the Royal Family, at 2.45 pm.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Fifteen minutes later the competitors entered the stadium in a procession that took 50 minutes.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The last team was that of the United Kingdom.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] A visionary dream has today become a glorious reality.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] At the end of the worldwide struggle in 1945, many institutions and associations were found to have withered and only the strongest had survived.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] How, many wondered, had the great Olympic Movement prospered?
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] At 4 pm, the time shown on the clock tower on the London Games symbol, the King declared the Games open, 2,500 pigeons were set free and the Olympic Flag raised to its 35 ft (11 m) flagpole at the end of the stadium.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The Royal Horse Artillery sounded a 21-gun salute to welcome the last runner in the Torch Relay: John Mark, a British track and field sprinter and student at the University of Cambridge with impressive Olympian good looks.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Mark ran a lap of the track – created with cinders from the domestic coal fires of Leicester – and climbed the steps to the Olympic cauldron.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] After saluting the crowd, he turned and lit the flame.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] After more speeches, Donald Finlay of the British team (given his RAF rank of Wing Commander) took the Olympic Oath on behalf of all competitors.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The National Anthem was sung and the massed athletes turned and marched out of the stadium, led by Greece, tailed by Britain.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Thus were launched the Olympic Games of London, under the most happy auspices.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony and over 60 hours of Games coverage was broadcast live on BBC television, which was then officially available only in the London area.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] However, the BBC's transmissions could be received much further away in the right conditions, and some of the Games were watched by at least one viewer in the Channel Islands.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The BBC's official report on the coverage estimated that an average of half a million viewers watched each of their Olympic broadcasts.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The BBC paid £1,000 for the broadcasting rights.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Of the live television coverage, only a small section of the opening ceremony broadcast still exists in the archives.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] However, various filmed reports shot for the BBC's *Television Newsreel* program do also still exist.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Summer Olympics featured 136 medal events, covering 23 disciplines in 17 different sports and in arts.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] These Games also included Lacrosse and Swedish (Ling) gymnastics as demonstration sports.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Empire Stadium was the venue for 33 athletics events at the Games; 24 for men and nine for women.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Of these, four were making their Olympic debut – the men's 10 km walk, and the women's 200 metres, long jump and shot put.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] A total of 754 athletes from 53 countries participated in athletics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Fanny Blankers-Koen of the Netherlands, a 30-year-old mother of two children nicknamed "The Flying Housewife", won four gold medals, in the 100 metres, 200 metres, 80 metre hurdles, and 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] As world record holder in the long jump and high jump Blankers-Koen may have been able to win further medals but, at this time, female athletes were limited to three individual events.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Duncan White won the first medal of any kind for Sri Lanka (then Ceylon) when he finished second in the 400 metre hurdles.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Arthur Wint became the first Jamaican to win an Olympic gold medal, in the men's 400 metres; he also won silver in the men's 800 metres.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Audrey Patterson became the first African-American woman to win a medal, winning bronze in a track and field event.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] A few days later Alice Coachman became the first woman of colour in the world and the first African-American woman to win a gold medal in track and field in the history of the modern Olympics with a jump of 1.68 m (5' 61⁄4").
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] She also was the only American woman to win an athletics gold medal during the 1948 Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The marathon saw a dramatic finish with the first man to enter the stadium, Etienne Gailly of Belgium, exhausted and nearly unable to run.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] While he was struggling, Argentinian athlete Delfo Cabrera and Tom Richards of Great Britain passed him, with Cabrera winning the gold medal and Richards obtaining the silver.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Gailly managed to recover enough to cross the line for the bronze.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The decathlon was won by 17-year-old Bob Mathias of the United States.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Categories: sports-related architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] These Olympics were the last time art competitions were considered Olympic events.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Basketball made its second appearance as a medal sport, appearing as an indoor competition for the first time after poor weather disrupted the matches at the 1936 Berlin Games.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The event, for men only, was contested by 23 nations split into four pools for the preliminary round; the top two in each pool advanced to the quarterfinals with the other teams entering playoffs for the minor placings.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The United States and France reached the final which was won by the Americans 65–21 to claim the gold medal.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] This was the second of the United States' seven consecutive gold medals in Olympic men's and women's basketball.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Brazil defeated Mexico 52–47 to claim bronze.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Eight different classifications were contested ranging from flyweight, for boxers weighing less than 51 kg, to heavyweight, for boxers over 80 kg.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] South Africa, Argentina and Hungary each won two gold medals.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Nine events were contested, eight for men and one for women.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that a women's canoeing event had been contested in the Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Sweden won four gold medals (two by Gert Fredriksson) and Czechoslovakia three.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Six events were contested – two road bicycle racing events and four track cycling events.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] No women's cycling events were contested.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] France won three gold medals and Italy two, while Great Britain captured five medals overall, but none were gold.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Four diving events were contested, two for men, and two for women.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The events are labelled as 3 metre springboard and 10 metre platform by the International Olympic Committee but appeared on the 1948 Official Report as *springboard diving* and *highboard diving*, respectively.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] All four gold medals, and 10 out of 12 awarded in total, were won by the United States.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Victoria Manalo Draves, who won both gold medals in the women's events, and Sammy Lee, who took a gold and a bronze in the men's events, became the first Asian Americans to win gold medals at an Olympic Games.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Six gold medals were awarded in equestrian, individual and team dressage, individual and team eventing and individual and team show jumping.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Harry Llewellyn and Foxhunter, who would claim a gold medal in Helsinki, won bronze in the team jumping event.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Seven events were contested, six for men and one for women.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Ilona Elek, who had won the women's foil competition in Berlin, was one of only two competitors to successfully defend an Olympic title in London.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Elek's sister, Margit, placed sixth in the same event.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Edoardo Mangiarotti won three medals, two silver and a bronze, having previously won a gold medal in the 1936 Games.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Throughout his career the Italian won 13 Olympic fencing medals and 27 world championship medals, both of which remain records.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Thirteen nations participated in the field hockey competition.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The tournament was ultimately won by India, who defeated Great Britain to claim the country's first gold medal as an independent nation under captain Kishan Lal and Vice-Captain Kunwar Digvijay Singh.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Eighteen teams entered the football competition at these Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Due to the rise of the professional game during the 12 years since the Berlin Olympics the number of talented amateurs for teams to select from was reduced.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The gold medal was won by Sweden, who defeated Yugoslavia 3–1 in the final.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Denmark defeated hosts Great Britain, managed by Matt Busby of Manchester United, 5–3 to win the bronze medal.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the tournament's 18 matches a total of 102 goals were scored; an average 5.66 goals per match.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The joint top scorers with seven goals each were Gunnar Nordahl of Sweden and Denmark's John Hansen.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Nordahl and Swedish teammates Gunnar Gren and Nils Liedholm went on to play for A.C.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Milan and together were nicknamed Gre-No-Li.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] This was the first international football tournament ever to be broadcast on television, with the two semi-finals, the bronze medal match and the final all being shown live in full by the BBC.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Nine events were contested, eight for men, and one for women.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the men's pommel horse, a tie was declared between three competitors, all Finns, and no medals other than gold were awarded in this event.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Finland won six gold medals overall, and Switzerland three.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Lacrosse was an exhibition sport at these Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] An English team composed of players from various universities played a U.S. team represented by Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute at the Empire Stadium.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Only one modern pentathlon event was contested, the five component sports– riding, fencing, shooting, swimming, and running- being held over six days.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Scoring was by point-for-place system across the five phases with the winner being the athlete with the lowest combined ranking.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The sport's international federation, the Union Internationale de Pentathlon Moderne was founded during the Games, on 3 August 1948.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Sweden won two medals in the event; William Grut won the gold, with a final points total of 16, and Gösta Gärdin took bronze.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] American George Moore won the silver medal.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Seven rowing events were contested, all open to men only.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Great Britain and the United States each claimed two gold medals.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The events were held on the River Thames at Henley, over the same course as the Henley Royal Regatta.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The sailing events at the Games took place in Torquay, in the southwest of Great Britain.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Five events were contested, with the United States winning four total medals.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] One of host nation Great Britain's three gold medals at the Games came in the Swallow class from Stewart Morris and David Bond.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the Firefly class Danish sailor Paul Elvstrøm won gold the despite the Danish Olympic Committee having misgivings about sending him to compete as the 18-year-old could speak no English.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] This was the first of four consecutive Olympics with a gold medal for Elvstrøm.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Four events were contested, all open to both men and women, although all medals were won by men.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the 50 metre rifle, prone position, only two points separated the top three competitors.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Károly Takács had been a member of the Hungary's world champion pistol shooting team in 1938 when a grenade shattered his right hand – his pistol hand.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Takács taught himself to shoot with his left hand and, 10 years after his injury, he won an Olympic gold medal in the rapid-fire pistol event.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Eleven events were contested, six for men and five for women.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The United States won eight gold medals, including all six men's events, and 15 medals in total.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Eighteen nations fielded a team in these games, which were ultimately won by Italy, who were undefeated throughout.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The tournament was conducted in a mult-tier bracket, with the best four teams from the group stages participating in a final round-robin bracket.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Silver was claimed by Hungary, and bronze by the Netherlands.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Six events were contested, all for men only.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] These games marked the addition of the bantamweight class to the Olympic programme, the first change to the programme since 1920.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The United States won four gold medals, and eight overall; the remaining two gold medals were claimed by Egypt.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Sixteen wrestling events were held, eight Greco-Roman and eight freestyle.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Both categories were dominated by two nations.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Turkey was the most successful nation with six gold medals followed by Sweden receiving 5 gold medals.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] These two teams claimed 24 total medals, in other words half of the total medals given.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] London was the first Olympics to have a political defection.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Marie Provazníková, the 57-year-old Czechoslovak President of the International Gymnastics Federation, refused to return home, citing "lack of freedom" after the Czechoslovak coup in February led to the country's inclusion in the Soviet Bloc.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] For the 1948 Olympics, the Technicolor Corporation devised a bipack colour filming process – dubbed "Technichrome" – whereby hundreds of hours of film documented the events in colour, without having to use expensive and heavy Technicolor cameras.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Slightly over 2,000 journalists attended the 1948 Games.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] A cinder track was laid inside Empire Stadium and all other venues were adapted.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] For the first time at the Olympics swimming events were held undercover, at the 8000 capacity Empire Pool.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] As the pool was longer than the standard Olympic length of 50 metres a platform was constructed across the pool which both shortened it and housed officials.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In 2010 one of the last remaining venues from the Games, the Herne Hill Velodrome where cycling events were staged, was saved when a new 15-year lease was agreed meaning that repairs could take place.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Campaigners and users of the track had feared that it would be forced to close as it was in desperate need of refurbishment.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Thirteen made their first official appearance: British Guiana (now Guyana), Burma (now Myanmar), Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), Iraq, Jamaica, Korea, Lebanon, Pakistan, Puerto Rico, Singapore, Syria, Trinidad and Tobago, and Venezuela.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] It was the first time that Australia, New Zealand, Philippines, India and Pakistan competed as fully independent nations at the Olympic Games.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Germany and Japan, under Allied military occupations, were not allowed to send athletes to the games.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Due to continuing labour shortages, German prisoners of war were used for the construction of the facilities for the games, in particular Olympic Way.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Italy, although originally an Axis power, had defected to the Allies in 1943 following Benito Mussolini being deposed, and was allowed to send athletes.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union was invited but chose not to send any athletes, sending observers instead to prepare for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The nations that returned to the games were Cuba, Iran (The last participation of a Persian athlete was in Paris 1900), Ireland, Panama and Spain.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Other nations, besides Germany and Japan, that participated in the previous games in Berlin 1936 but were absent in London 1948 were Bolivia, Bulgaria, Costa Rica, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the case of the Baltic nations, they had been occupied and annexed by the Soviet Union, only returning to the games many decades later.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Bulgaria, Romania and Mandatory Palestine accepted invitations for the Games but withdrew a few days before it began.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Puerto Rico, an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States, made its Olympic debut as an independent team.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] Bermuda, Jamaica, Trinidad and Tobago, Singapore and British Guyana were part of the British Empire.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1948 Summer Games, ranked by number of gold medals won.
[src:asian-games/1948-summer-olympics] The host nation was 12th, with 27 medals, including four golds.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The **1951 Asian Games**, officially known as the **First Asian Games** (Hindi: प्रथम एशियाई खेल), were a multi-sport event celebrated in New Delhi, India from 4 to 11 March 1951.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] A total of 489 athletes representing 11 Asian National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated in 57 events from eight sports and discipline.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The Games was the successor of the Far Eastern Games and the revival of the Western Asiatic Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The 1951 Asiad were originally scheduled to be held in 1950, but postponed until 1951 due to delays in preparations.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] On 13 February 1949, the Asian Games Federation was formally established in Delhi, with Delhi unanimously announced as the first host city of the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The games were managed by a strong Organizing Committee (see Organization below).
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Countries invited included almost all the independent Asian countries of the time except Soviet Union (as they were part of the European Olympic Committees) and Vietnam, due to the political structure of those nations.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] National Stadium was the venue for all events.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The official logo of the First Asiad depicted a bright sun in red with 16 rays and a white circle in the middle of the disc of the sun and eleven rings, representing each participating nation, on a white background, symbolising peace.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Japanese athletes won the 24 gold, 21 silver, and 15 bronze medals, respectively; while the host nation India had 15 golds and 51 overall medals with most bronzes (20) and finished at second spot in a medal table.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The next Asian Games organised by India were the 1982 Asian Games, some 31 years later.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The 1951 Asian Games are considered to be a successor of a small-scale multi-sport event known as the Far Eastern Games, held in between a period of 1913 to 1938 in the different cities of Japan, Philippines, and mainland China.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The First Far Eastern Games took place in Manila, Philippines in 1913, after the efforts made by the Philippine Amateur Athletic Federation (PAAF).
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] During the starting years of the 1930s, efforts were made to organize a multi-sport event to include the countries of West Asia too, this gave a birth to "Orient Championship Games", which later renamed as Western Asiatic Games before its first inception.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The scope of the Games comprised all the countries east of Suez and west of Singapore.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The First Western Asiatic Games was celebrated in Delhi in 1934 at the Irwin Amphitheater, in which four countries—Afghanistan, British India, Palestine Mandate and Ceylon—participated.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The decision was made to hold these Games once in four years at midpoint between the two successive Summer Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The 1938 Western Asiatic Games were scheduled to be held in Tel Aviv, Palestine Mandate.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] However, the Games was cancelled due to the outbreak of World War II, and abandoned until 1951 Games, which also considered as the revival of Western Asiatic Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] On 12 and 13 February 1949, a meeting was organized at the Patiala House, in Delhi, in between the representatives of nine Asian National Olympic Committees.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The framework of the meeting was set up in another meeting held on 8 August 1948 during the Second London Olympics, which was called by the Indian Olympic Committee's representative Guru Dutt Sondhi.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The meeting was chaired by Yadavindra Singh, president of the Indian Olympic Association.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] On the last day, Asian Games Federation (AGF)[b] was formalized and a draft constitution was accepted.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] HRH Yadavindra Singh and Guru Dutt Sondhi were respectively elected as the first president and the secretary of the federation.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The five charter members forming the federation were Afghanistan, Burma, India, Pakistan, and the Philippines.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The decision was made to organize the Asian Games Championships in four-year intervals since the inception of the Games in Delhi in February, 1950.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] HRH Yadavindra Singh, who also became the president of the organization committee of Games sent the formal invitation to several other Asian countries to participate in the 1950 Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Bhoot, Nariman Saugar who did much work with the stadium, and others.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The principal Executive members were: Director of Organisation Anthony de Mello; Secretary to the Director S.S.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Sequeira; Assistant Secretary Nariman S.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] An athletes' camp was settled in Delhi, modelled after the Richmond Park Camp of London, which accommodated athletes of the 1948 Summer Olympics.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The venue for the 1951 Asian Games was the Irwin Amphitheater, a multi-purpose sport complex, the same venue which had hosted the 1934 Western Asiatic Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Before the opening ceremony of the Games, the stadium was re-christened as the "National Stadium" and renovated for the facilities of different events of the Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Every event with the exception of swimming and water polo was hosted under the premises of the main stadium only, the events of swimming and water polo were organised at the adjacent swimming pool within the premises of the complex.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] DeMello and five-hundred thousand (500,000) rupees were required for the full construction, which was completed on 13 February 1933.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The stadium was named after the Lord Irwin, 30th viceroy of India and the then Secretary of State for War.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The Games featured six sports: Athletics, aquatics—broken into Diving, swimming, and water polo disciplines—basketball, cycling—road cycling and track cycling—football, and weightlifting.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The sports were broken down into 57 events.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Many member countries of Asian Games Federation requested for the inclusion of boxing as a medal sport, but due to various reasons, boxing did not make the final list for the Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Except athletics, women did not participate in any other event.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Asia of 1951" was also contested as the non-medal event.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The contingents were judged on the basis of their physical development, looks, and personality.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Parimal Roy of India won the event ahead of Mahmoud Namjoo of Iran, who won gold medal in the bantamweight category of weightlifting.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In diving, two medal events—3 m springboard and 10 m platform—were included.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] India and Iran were the only nations that achieved medals.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Thakkar won both the golds and overall India won 4 medals.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Iran bagged only one silver and one bronze.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In swimming, five nations sent their swimmers to participate in 8 events, 5 of freestyle (100 m, 400 m, 800 m, 1500 m, and 4 × 100 m relay) and one of each backstroke (100 m), breaststroke (200 m) and medley (3 × 100 m).
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] After these Games, 800 m freestyle and 3 × 100 m medley relay were removed from the swimming calendar of Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Singapore bagged half of gold medals and 2 silvers, while Philippines earned half of total medals including 3 golds, India finished with 6 total medals including one gold of Sachin Nag in 100 m freestyle, which was the first gold of India in Asian Games; two nations left without any medal.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In water polo, only two teams—India and Singapore—participated.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The only match of the tournament decided the winner, in which the Indian team defeated Singapore with a goal difference of 6 to 4.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Athletics was the only sport in which all the eleven participating nations sent their athletes.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The Games featured 24 medal events for men and 9 for women.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Japanese women won all the 9 golds of their events and just lost four silvers to India and Singapore, two for each.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In men's events, again Japan achieved highest number of golds with count of 11, but here Indian athletes finished just one medal behind to Japan with 10 golds.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Toyoko Yoshino, a Japanese woman athlete, won all the golds in three throwing sports— shot put, discus throw, and javelin throw.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Lavy Pinto of India was the only man who achieved multiple gold medals, he finished at the top podium in men's 100 m and 200 m sprint running events.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In basketball, five Asian teams—Burma, India, Iran, Japan, and Philippines—participated.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In the matches, the round-robin format was employed and on the basis of final points table top three podium places were decided.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Philippines team without losing a single match topped the points table and grabbed a gold medal, Japan team finished behind it and won a silver medal, Iranian team with two wins finished third and won a bronze.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Host nation India, finished fourth with only single win over Burma, which came last without winning a single match.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Winning Japanese and Indian team on podium for medal ceremony.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In cycling, four nations—Burma, India, Iran, and Japan—sent their cyclists.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Two disciplines—road race and track race—were contested.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Track cycling included—1000 m sprint, 1000 m time trial, and 4000 team-pursuit; for road cycling, 180 km individual road race was contested.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The event was widely perceived as being dominated by Japan, who claimed 8 medals in total, including all the four golds out of 11 total overall medals and 4 golds.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Indian cyclists won all the rest 3 medals as Burma and Iran failed to achieve a single one.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In football, six Asian teams—Afghanistan, Burma, India, Indonesia, Iran, and Japan—participated.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The gold medal was won by the Indian team, who defeated Iran 1–0 in the final.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Japan defeated Afghanistan, 2–0 to win the bronze medal.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In weightlifting, seven countries participated in seven events—bantamweight (56 kg), featherweight (60 kg), lightweight (67.5 kg), middleweight (75 kg), light heavyweight (82.5 kg), middle heavyweight (90 kg), and heavyweight (+90 kg).
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Iranian weightlifters dominated in all events and claimed 10 medals in total including all the golds, Singapore won two silvers, while both India and Philippines won one silver and one bronze.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 1951 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport were held.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The numeral indicates the number of event finals for each sport held that day.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] On the left, the calendar lists each sport with events held during the Games, and at the right, how many gold medals were won in that sport.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] There is a key at the top of the calendar to aid the reader.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] On 4 March 1951, the First Asian Games were officially opened.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The list of the guests included— India's first President Rajendra Prasad, first Prime Minister of India Jawaharlal Nehru, cabinet members of Indian Government, diplomatic corps and representatives of participating Asian NOCs.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The National Stadium was filled with an estimated 40,000 spectators.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] A 31-gun salute was fired from the ramparts of the Purana Quila, adjacent to the National Stadium, in the honour of guests and participants of first Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] After a speech by the president of Asian Games Federation, HRH Yadavendra Singh, President Rajendra Prashad officially opened the Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Prime Minister Nehru presented his speech from which organisers of the Games adopted the official motto of the Games— "Play the game, in the spirit of the game".
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Fifteen of the Indian army's trumpeters with flags of eleven participating countries on their mastheads gave their performance.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] In an alphabetical order of English, athletes of the participating countries of the 1951 Asiad entered in the stadium with a march past, by following the custom of Olympics; India entered last as the host nation.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The Lighting of the Cauldron was done by the 1924 Olympian of India, Dalip Singh with the help of Asian Games torch, which had been lit by the sun's rays in the Red Fort.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Afterwards, Baldev Singh, a member of the Indian athletics squad, recited the athlete's oath on behalf of all competitors at the Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The 1951 Asiad featured athletes representing 11 National Olympic Committees.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The Organising Committee of the Games sent the formal invitations to almost all the Asian countries.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] China was invited, but did not respond before the closing dates for entries.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Pakistan declined to participate because of the Kashmir conflict with India.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] South Korea attended the meeting of Olympic representatives of Asian countries, held on 8 August 1948, during the London Olympics and agreed to send athletes for Games to participate but did not send any because of the Korean War.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The Soviet Union and Vietnam were not invited because of their political systems.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Japan was neither invited to the 1948 Summer Olympics nor to attend the founding meeting of Asian Games Federation held in February 1949 in Delhi, but allowed to participate in these Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Japan sent a 72-member strong team, the second largest after the host, and participated in all except aquatics events.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Burma and India sent their contingents in all the events.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Iran participated in all events, but did not send any female athletes.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Athletes from eight participating NOCs won at least one medal, five of them winning at least one gold medal.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Athletes from Japan earned the highest number of gold medals (24) and the most overall medals (60).
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Host nation India finished second with 15 golds and 51 overall medals as well as the most bronzes (20).
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Through 2010, it would be the best rank achieved by India in medal table in all succeeding Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Iran finished third with 8 golds and 16 overall medals.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Three NOCs, Afghanistan, Nepal, and Thailand failed to earn any medals.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] Singaporean swimmer Neo Chwee Kok earned the honour of winning the first gold medal in the history of the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] He won a total of four golds, all in the free style events (400m, 800m, 1500m, and 4 × 100m relay); becoming the most medalled athlete in this Games.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The ranking in this table is consistent with International Olympic Committee convention in its published medal tables.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won (in this context, a nation is an entity represented by a National Olympic Committee).
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next, and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] If nations are still tied, equal ranking is given; they are listed alphabetically by IOC country code.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] A total of 169 medals (57 gold, 57 silver and 55 bronze) were awarded.
[src:asian-games/1951-asian-games] The total number of bronze medals is less than the total number of gold or silver medals because bronze medals were not awarded in water polo and the team pursuit event of track cycling.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The **1954 Asian Games** (Filipino: *Palarong Asyano 1954*), officially known as the **Second Asian Games** – **Manila 1954**, were a multi-sport event held in Manila, Philippines, from May 1 to 9, 1954.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] A total of 970 athletes from 19 Asian National Olympic Committees (NOCs) competed in 76 events from eight sports.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The number of participating NOCs and athletes were larger than the previous Asian Games held in New Delhi in 1951.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] This edition of the games has a different twist where it did not implement a medal tally system to determine the overall champion but a pointing system.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The pointing system is a complex system where each athlete were given points according to their achievement like position in athletics or in swimming.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] In the end the pointing system showed to be worthless as it simply ranked the nations the same way in the medal tally system.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The pointing system was not implemented in future games ever since.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] Vargas was the head of the Philippine Amateur Athletic Federation (now known as Philippine Olympic Committee since 1976) and the Manila Asian Games Organizing Committee.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] With the second-place finish of the Philippines, only around 9,000 spectators attended the closing ceremony at the Rizal Memorial Stadium.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The events were broadcast on radio live at DZRH and DZAQ-TV ABS-3 on delayed telecast.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The Games were formally opened by President Ramon Magsaysay on May 1, 1954, at 16:02 local time.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] Around 20,000 spectators filled the Rizal Memorial Stadium in Malate, Manila, for the opening ceremony.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] As requested by the IOC, the torch relay and lighting of the cauldron were excluded from the Opening Ceremony to preserve the tradition of the Olympic Games.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The torch ceremony were returned at the 1958 Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The host however gave a solution by giving a special citation to the last athlete to enter the parade.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The Philippines, as host, was the last country to enter the stadium.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The flag bearer for the Philippines squad was Andres Franco, who won a gold medal in the 1951 Asian Games in high jump event, the sole gold medal of any Filipino in the athletics events of the previous Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The 1954 Asian Games featured eight sports divided into 10 events, aquatics included three events namely diving, swimming and water polo.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] This version of the Asian Games comprised more sports and events than the last one, as six sports and seven events were in the calendar of 1951 Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] Three sports—boxing, shooting and wrestling—made their debut, while cycling was dropped out.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] National Olympic Committees (NOCs) are named and arranged according to their official IOC country codes and designations at the time.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 1954 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] Japan led the medal table, athletes from Japan won most medals, including most gold, silver and bronze.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] Host nation, Philippines finished second with 45 total medals (including 14 gold).
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:asian-games/1954-asian-games] The host nation, Philippines, is highlighted.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The **1958 Asian Games**, officially the **Third Asian Games** (Japanese: 第3回アジア競技大会) and commonly known as **Tokyo 1958** (Japanese: 東京1958), were a multi-sport event held in Tokyo, Japan, from 24 May to 1 June 1958.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] It was governed by the Asian Games Federation.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] A total of 1,820 athletes representing 20 Asian National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated in the Games.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The program featured competitions in 13 different sports encompassing 97 events, including four non-Olympic sports, judo, table tennis, tennis and volleyball.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] Four of these competition sports – field hockey, table tennis, tennis and volleyball – were introduced for the first time in the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] This is the first time that Japan hosted the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The Asian Games is a multi-sport event, much like the Summer Olympics (albeit on a much smaller scale), with participation exclusively for Asian countries.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The first edition was held in the capital city of India, New Delhi, in 1951, attracting 489 competitors from 11 nations.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The programme for the Tokyo 1958 Games included 13 different sports divided into 97 events.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] Four of these sports – judo, table tennis, tennis and volleyball – were not on the official Olympic sports programme at that time.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] Badminton was added as a demonstration sport, which, from 1962 onwards, became a regular competitive sport in the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The tradition of torch relay, inspired by the Olympic Games, was introduced for the first time in the Asian Games in 1958.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The relay officially began from the main venue of the Second Asian Games, Rizal Memorial Coliseum, in Manila, Philippines.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] In the host nation, Japan, it was relayed from Okinawa to Kyushu Island.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] Okinawa was under the United States administration at that time.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] At the opening ceremony, the Games cauldron was ignited by the first Japanese Olympic gold medallist and the first Asian Olympic champion in an individual event, Mikio Oda.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] A record total of 1,820 athletes representing 20 member nations of the Asian Games Federation participated in the Games.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The number of participating countries was also greatest in comparison to the first two editions of the Games.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The Thai delegation held a meeting on 22 May 1958 in Tokyo, and invitations were sent to the representatives of Malaysia, Burma and Laos.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The agenda of the meeting was to discuss the possibility of forming a regional multi-sport event on the lines of Asian Games for the countries of Southeast Asia.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] This way the Southeast Asian Peninsular Games (SEAP Games), which later became the Southeast Asian Games, were established and the first SEAP Games were held in Bangkok, Thailand, in 1959.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The opening ceremony of the Tokyo 1958 Games was organised on 24 May 1958 at the National Olympic Stadium.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The ceremony, among other dignitaries and guests, included the Emperor of Japan Hirohito, crown prince Akihito and Shah of Iran Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] Around 70,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 1958 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] Athletes from 16 countries won medals, leaving four countries without a medal, and 11 of them won at least one gold medal.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] Afghanistan, Cambodia, Nepal and North Borneo did not win any medal.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The Japanese 4 × 100 metres medley relay team of Keiji Hase (backstroke), Masaru Furukawa (breaststroke), Manabu Koga (freestyle) and Takashi Ishimoto (butterfly) won the gold medal with a time of 4:17.2 and broke the world record.
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won (in this context, a nation is an entity represented by a NOC).
[src:asian-games/1958-asian-games] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next, followed by the number of bronze medals.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The **Asian Games**, also known as **Asiad**, is a continental multi-sport event held every four years for athletes of Asia.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Games were regulated by Asian Games Federation from the first Games in New Delhi, India in 1951, until the 1978 Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Since the 1982 Games, they have been organized by the Olympic Council of Asia, after the breakup of the Asian Games Federation.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Games are recognized by the International Olympic Committee and are the second largest multi-sport event after the Olympic Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Nine nations have hosted the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Forty-six nations have participated in the Games, including Israel, which was excluded from the Games after its last participation in 1974.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The last edition of the Games was held in Hangzhou, China, from 23 September to 8 October 2023.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The next edition will be held in Aichi Prefecture and Nagoya, Japan, from 19 September to 4 October 2026.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Since 2010, it has been common for the host of the Asian Games to host the Asian Para Games held shortly after the end of the Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] This event is exclusive to athletes with disabilities, just like Paralympic Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] But unlike the Paralympics where the host city's contract mentions the holding of both events, the case of Asia does not mention the mandatory holding of both.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Instead, the exclusion of the Asian Paralympic Games from the Asian Games host city's contract means that both events run independently from one other, and may lead to occasions in the future when the two events are held in different cities and countries.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Far Eastern Championship Games existed previous to the Asian Games, the former mooted in 1912 for a location set between Japan, the Philippines, and China.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The inaugural Far Eastern Games were held in Manila in 1913 with 6 participating nations.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] There were ten Far Eastern Games held by 1934.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The second Sino-Japanese War in 1934, and Japan's insistence on including the Manchu Empire as a competitor nation in the Games, caused China to announce its withdrawal from participation.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Far Eastern Games scheduled for 1938 were cancelled.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The organization was eventually discontinued.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] After World War II, several areas in Asia became sovereign states.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Many of these countries sought to exhibit Asian prowess without violence.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] During the 1948 Summer Olympics in London, a conversation started between China and the Philippines to restore the idea of the Far Eastern Games, following the decolonisation of Asia after World War II.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Guru Dutt Sondhi, the Indian International Olympic Committee representative, believed that the restoration of the Far Eastern Games would sufficiently display the spirit of unity and level of achievement taking place in Asian sports.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] He proposed the idea of a new competition – which came to be the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Asian Athletic Federation would eventually be formed.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] A preparatory committee was set up to draft the charter for this new body.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] On 13 February 1949, the Asian Athletic Federation was formally inaugurated in New Delhi, announced as the inaugural host city to be held in 1950.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] In 1962, the Games were hit by several crises.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The host country, Indonesia refused to permit Israel and Taiwan to participate due to political recognition issues.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The IOC terminated its sponsorship of the Games and terminated Indonesia's membership in the IOC.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Asian Football Confederation (AFC), International Amateur Athletics Federation (IAAF), and the International Weightlifting Federation (IWF) also removed their recognition of the Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Seoul renounced its plan to host the 1970 Asian Games on the grounds of a national security crisis; the main reason was due to a financial crisis.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The previous host, Thailand, would host the Games in Bangkok using funds transferred from South Korea.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Japan was asked to host but declined the opportunity as they were already committed to Expo '70 in Osaka.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] This edition marked the Games' inaugural television broadcasting, worldwide.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] In Tehran, in 1974, the Games formally recognized the participation of China, North Korea, and Mongolia.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Israel was allowed to participate despite the opposition from the Arab world, while Taiwan was permitted to continue taking part (as "Chinese Taipei") although its status was abolished in a general meeting on 16 November 1973 by the Games Federation.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Before the 1978 Games, Pakistan retracted its plan to host the 1978 Games due to a financial crisis and political issues.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Thailand offered to host and the Games were held in Bangkok.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] As in 1962, Taiwan and Israel refused participation by the Games Federation, amid political issues and security fears.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Several governing bodies protested the ban.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The International Olympic Committee threatened to bar the participating athletes from the 1980 Summer Olympics.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Several nations withdrew before the Games opening.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] These events led the National Olympic Committees in Asia to revise the constitution of the Asian Games Federation.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Olympic Council of Asia was created in November 1981, excluding Israel and Taiwan.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] India was scheduled to host in 1982 and the OCA decided to maintain the old AGF timetable.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The OCA formally started to supervise the Games starting with the 1986 Asian Games scheduled for Seoul, South Korea.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] In the 1990 Asian Games held in Beijing, Taiwan (Republic of China) was re-admitted, under pressure by the People's Republic of China to compete as *Chinese Taipei*.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The 1994 Games held in Hiroshima included the inaugural participation of the former 5 republics of the Soviet Union who were part of Central Asia: Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, and Uzbekistan.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] It was also the first edition of the Games held in a host country outside its capital city.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] However, Iraq was suspended from the Games due to the 1990 Persian Gulf War.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] North Korea boycotted the Games due to political issues with the host country.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Games were hampered during the opening ceremony due to a heart attack that killed Nareshkumar Adhikari, the chief of the Nepalese delegation.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The 1998 Games marked the fourth time the Games were held in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] This time the city participated in a bidding process.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The opening ceremony was on 6 December; the previous three were on 9 December.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] King Bhumibol Adulyadej opened the Games; the closing ceremony was on 20 December (the same date as all the previous games hosted by Thailand).
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Asian Games Movement uses symbols to represent the ideals embodied in the Asian Games charter.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Asian Games motto is "Ever Onward" which was designed and proposed by Guru Dutt Sondhi upon the creation of the Asian Games Federation in 1949.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Asian Games symbol is a bright sun in red with 16 rays and a white circle in the middle of its disc which represents the ever glimmering and warm spirit of the Asian people.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Since the 1982 Asian Games in New Delhi, India, the Asian Games have had a mascot, usually an animal native to the area or occasionally human figures representing the cultural heritage.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] All 45 members affiliated with the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) are eligible to participate in the Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] According to membership in the OCA, transcontinental Kazakhstan is an Asian country and could participate in the Asian Games, but this right could not apply to Egypt as the country had 6% of the territory on Sinai, participating in the African Games instead.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Turkey and Russia/Soviet Union — whose major geographical parts are located in the Asian continent — participate in the European Games rather than the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Similarly, Azerbaijan, Georgia, Cyprus, and Armenia are mostly located in Asia but participate in the European Games instead of the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] In history, 46 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) have sent competitors to the Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Israel has been excluded from the Games since 1976, the reason cited as being due to security reasons.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Israel requested to participate in the 1982 Games, but the request was rejected by the organizers due to the Munich massacre.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Israel is now a member of the European Olympic Committees (EOC) since 1994 and competes at the European Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Taiwan, Palestine, Hong Kong, and Macau participate in the Asian Games according to membership in OCA.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Due to its continuing ambiguous political status, Taiwan has participated in the Games under the flag of Chinese Taipei since 1990.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Macau since 1990 has been allowed to compete as one of the NOCs in the Asian Games, despite not being recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) for participation in the Olympic Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] In 2007, the President of OCA, Sheikh Ahmed Al-Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, rejected the proposal to allow Australia to participate in the Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] He stated that while Australia would add good value to the Asian Games, it would be unfair to the Oceania National Olympic Committees (ONOC).
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Being members of ONOC, Australia and New Zealand have participated in the Pacific Games since 2015.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] This motion was mooted again in 2017 after Australia participated in the 2017 Asian Winter Games as they are in discussions to become a full Asian Games member shortly.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] However, the Australian Olympic Committee announced that Australia would be allowed a small contingent of athletes for the 2022 Games, as long as the qualification for Summer Olympics events such as basketball and volleyball are through the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] In November 2021, it was announced that athletes from Oceania would be invited to compete in athletics, triathlon, roller skating, weightlifting, and wushu.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Athletes were to receive "honorary medals" which would not be counted on the official medal tally.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The plan was shelved due to a lack of interest from the relevant federations in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] There are only seven countries, namely India, Indonesia, Japan, the Philippines, Sri Lanka, Singapore, and Thailand, that have competed in all editions of the games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] 45 nations whose NOCs are recognized by the OCA compete at the Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The historical average for the edition of events by the edition of the Asian Games is nearly 260 events with nearly 24 sports by edition.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The last edition held in Hangzhou, China was the edition with the largest number of events when 481 finals in 40 sports were held.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Until the 2018 edition, each host country was allowed to set up the program respecting their local demands, which led to a dizzying growth of the event.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] However, this flexibility rule ruled out the entry of some Olympic sports such as the modern pentathlon and triathlon of the programs of some editions between 1986 and 2006.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] This flexibility also increased the number of athletes participating in each edition.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] However, it forced the event to be massive, as there was no calculation of athlete quotas per NOC.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] To avoid gigantism, OCA established a new policy to be applied starting the 2018 Asian Games, which limited the number of sports to be played at the Games to 40.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] This new rule is by the Olympic program for the subsequent edition of the Summer Olympic Games and if there is any prior change, the entity will necessarily follow it.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] However, each region that makes up the body can nominate a regional sport according to its demands.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Between one and two extra sports could also be included by organizing committees due to local demands.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] Of the 46 National Olympic Committees participating throughout the history of the Games, 43 have won at least a single medal in the competition, leaving three National Olympic Committees without a medal: Bhutan, Maldives, and Timor-Leste.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] 38 National Olympic Committees have won at least one gold medal (only Japan and India have done so at every Asian Games), while China and Japan are the only two NOCs to emerge as the top-ranked team in the medal tables.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] In the 2022 Games, India became the fourth nation in history after Japan, China, and South Korea to cross the 100-medal mark in one edition.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] China, together with Japan and South Korea became the first three countries to cross the overall 200-medal mark in one edition during the 1986 Asian Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] At the 2022 Games, China became the first NOC to surpass the threshold of 100 gold medals, 200 gold medals, 300 overall medals and 400 overall medals in a single edition.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The Most Valuable Player or MVP award was introduced in the 1998 Games in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The award was originally awarded to one individual.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] During the 2022 edition in Hangzhou, the Games started awarding to one male and one female athlete separately.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] On 8 November 2012, the OCA decided at its 31st General Assembly in Macau to create a special multi-sport event called the Asian Games Centennial Festival in celebration of the 100th anniversary of the Oriental Games, now known as the Far Eastern Championship Games.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] OCA awarded the Philippines the hosting rights as it was also the host 100 years previous.
[src:asian-games/asian-games] The event was originally scheduled to be held in Boracay, Malay, Aklan from 27 to 29 November 2013 but due to the events surrounding Typhoon Haiyan, it was moved to January 2014.
